---
import ContentLayout from '../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
export const prerender = true;

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: "What makes a coffee roaster 'specialty'?",
    a: "In the strict sense, specialty coffee is green coffee that has scored 80 points or above on the Specialty Coffee Association's 100-point cupping scale. Specialty roasters source coffee that meets this threshold, roast it with attention to origin character, and typically provide traceability back to the farm or cooperative. In practice, the word is sometimes used loosely in marketing. The most reliable indicators of a genuine specialty roaster are: stated sourcing relationships with specific farms or cooperatives, clearly listed origin and processing information on their bags, and demonstrated care in roasting that preserves rather than obscures the coffee's natural character."
  },
  {
    q: "Is freshly roasted coffee really better?",
    a: "Yes, meaningfully so. Coffee begins off-gassing carbon dioxide immediately after roasting and is at its best flavored peak between 4 and 21 days off-roast, depending on the origin and roast level. Grocery store coffee often has no roast date at all, and many bags at retail are 30 to 90 days past their roast date. Specialty roasters that ship fresh, roast-to-order coffee genuinely taste different and better than stale supermarket alternatives when brewed properly. The difference is most dramatic in light to medium roasts, where the nuanced fruit and floral notes disappear quickly with age."
  },
  {
    q: "How do I choose between single-origin and blended coffee?",
    a: "Single-origin coffee comes from one farm, cooperative, or defined region and is the better choice when you want to taste what a specific place tastes like. It is ideal for pour-over, aeropress, and other clean-cup brewing methods that let the origin character come through. Blends are intentionally designed for consistency across batches and often for specific brewing contexts like espresso, where a blend of coffees can provide a balance of sweetness, body, and acidity that no single origin delivers as reliably. Choose single-origin when curiosity about origin is the goal; choose a blend when consistency or espresso is the priority."
  },
  {
    q: "Which specialty coffee roaster is best for espresso?",
    a: "For espresso, Coffee Bros. is the strongest online option among the five roasters reviewed here, with a dedicated espresso blend built to pull well at standard parameters. Five Star Coffee Roasters also blends specifically for espresso and commercial coffee service contexts. Kona and Hawaiian coffees can be beautiful espresso bases but are expensive for daily espresso service. Volcanica's single-origin Ethiopian and Colombian coffees work well as espresso when pulled at 1:2.5 to 1:3 ratios with slightly longer preinfusion."
  },
  {
    q: "Are these affiliate links? Do you earn a commission?",
    a: "Yes, some links on this page are affiliate links. We earn a small commission from purchases made through them, at no additional cost to you. This does not affect our recommendations. We only include roasters we have evaluated independently. The commissions help us operate this site."
  }
];

